    <h1>UNO House Rules — Every Popular Variant, Explained</h1>
    <p class="page-subtitle">Seven-Zero, Jump-In, stacking, Force Play and more — what each rule does, and how to play every single one online for free.</p>

    <p>Every family plays UNO differently. The rules below are the most popular house variants in the world — and unlike the official card game, our free browser version has <strong>all of them built in</strong>. Create a room, pick <strong>Custom mode</strong>, and flip on whichever rules your table plays.</p>

    <h2>🔄 The Seven-Zero Rule</h2>
    <p>The famous hand-swapping rule: play a <strong>7</strong> and you swap your entire hand with any player you choose. Play a <strong>0</strong> and everyone passes their hand to the next player in the direction of play. One card can flip the whole game — the player about to win suddenly holds twelve cards.</p>

    <h2>⚡ Jump-In</h2>
    <p>Holding the <em>exact</em> same card as the top of the pile — same color, same number or symbol? Slam it down instantly, even when it's not your turn. Play jumps to you and continues from there. Fast fingers win games with this rule on.</p>

    <h2>➕ Stacking</h2>
    <p>The most argued-about rule in UNO: answering a Draw 2 with your own Draw 2 so the next player draws 4 (and so on). We support +2 stacking, +4 stacking, cross-stacking, and even Skip Dodge and Reverse Bounce to deflect a pile. It's a deep enough topic that it has <a href="/rules/stacking">its own page →</a></p>

    <h2>🎣 Draw to Match</h2>
    <p>No playable card? In official rules you draw one card and your turn can end. With Draw to Match, you keep drawing until you find a playable card. Turns are never wasted — but a bad streak can fill your hand fast.</p>

    <h2>👊 Force Play</h2>
    <p>If you can play a card, you <strong>must</strong> play it. No hiding your Wild for the perfect moment, no drawing to dodge putting down your last +4 on your friend. Honest UNO — brutally honest.</p>

    <h2>⚔️ Wild Challenge</h2>
    <p>From tournament rules: a Wild +4 is only "legal" if the player had no card matching the current color. Think they cheated? Challenge! If you're right, they draw the 4 instead of you. If you're wrong, you draw 6. Bluffing becomes part of the game.</p>

    <h2>🏅 Play for Places</h2>
    <p>Normally the round ends the moment someone wins. With Play for Places, the first player out takes 1st — and everyone else keeps playing for 2nd, 3rd, and beyond. Nobody sits out feeling robbed after one lucky Wild; every seat plays to the end.</p>

    <h2>💀 Elimination</h2>
    <p>Straight from <a href="/uno-no-mercy">No Mercy</a>: collect too many cards (25 by default, adjustable) and you're out of the game. The last player standing wins. Pairs terrifyingly well with stacking.</p>

    <h2>💥 Wild +8 &amp; 🔀 Shuffle Hands</h2>
    <p>Two extra card types the host can add to the deck: the <strong>Wild +8</strong> (a Draw 4's much angrier sibling) and <strong>Wild Shuffle Hands</strong>, which collects every player's cards, shuffles them together, and deals them back out evenly.</p>

    <h2>⏱️ Table Settings</h2>
    <p>Beyond card rules, the host also controls the starting hand size (3–10 cards), the turn timer (15–90 seconds), the UNO-call grace time, and the room size (2–20 players).</p>

    <h2>How to Turn House Rules On</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Go to the <a href="/play">Play page</a> and create a room (free, no signup).</li>
      <li>Select <strong>🛠️ Custom</strong> mode in the room settings.</li>
      <li>Toggle any rule — every player in the lobby sees the active rules before the game starts.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Want a preset instead? <a href="/game-modes">Classic and No Mercy modes</a> configure everything in one tap.</p>

